message_1:
In the Battle of the Sexes game, Tom and Jane each independently choose a location for their date night. If they choose the same place, they will both be happy and receive a payoff of 3. If they choose different places, Tom prefers to go to the sports bar and Jane prefers to go to the wine bar. They will each receive a payoff of 2 for going to their preferred location, but only a payoff of 1 for going to the other location. 

If Tom's payoff matrix is:
\begin{equation}
\begin{matrix}
& \textbf{Sports Bar} & \textbf{Wine Bar} \\
\textbf{Sports Bar} & 3,3 & 1,2 \\
\textbf{Wine Bar} & 2,1 & 1,1
\end{matrix}
\end{equation}

And Jane's payoff matrix is:
\begin{equation}
\begin{matrix}
& \textbf{Sports Bar} & \textbf{Wine Bar} \\
\textbf{Sports Bar} & 1,2 & 2,1 \\
\textbf{Wine Bar} & 1,1 & 3,3
\end{matrix}
\end{equation}

What is the Nash Equilibrium of this game?
